      <preface xml:id="preface">
        <title>Preface</title>
        <p>
          This book is about how to tell a good argument from a bad one.
        </p>
        <p>
          That sounds smaller than it is. Most of the disagreements that
          matter in a life — about politics, science, relationships, money,
          how to spend a weekend — turn out, when you look closely, to be
          disagreements about reasons. Someone offers a claim and a reason
          to believe it; you accept the package, or you push back. Doing
          that well is a skill, and like any skill it can be practiced,
          improved, and, on a bad day, lost track of. Logic is the
          practice.
        </p>
        <p>
          The book has four parts. Part I looks at arguments in the wild:
          how to recognize them, how to lay out their parts, how to spot
          the most common ways they go off the rails. Part II takes up
          <em>categorical</em> arguments — claims about whole categories
          of things, the territory of <q>all,</q> <q>some,</q> and
          <q>no</q> — and develops a visual method for testing them.
          Part III moves to <em>sentential</em> logic, where we trade
          English sentences for symbols and learn a small set of rules
          that, used carefully, can carry you across surprisingly long
          chains of reasoning. Part IV turns to <em>inductive</em>
          reasoning: arguments whose premises don't guarantee their
          conclusions but make them more or less likely. This is the kind
          of reasoning that runs most of science, most of medicine, and
          most of what you do when you make up your mind about anything
          based on evidence.
        </p>
        <p>
          A few practical notes.
        </p>
        <p>
          The exercises give you practice; you need to practice. Logic is
          one of those subjects where the lecture can make perfect sense
          in the room and then evaporate by Thursday morning if you
          haven't actually used it on a few problems. The end-of-section
          exercises are short and meant to be done as you read. The
          end-of-chapter exercises are longer. The occasional
          <em>Field Exercises</em> ask you to leave the book and go
          listen, watch, or read for arguments in the world; please try
          them. Logic learned only on the page tends to stay on the page.
        </p>
        <p>
          Where the book uses external tools — an argument reconstruction
          editor, a natural deduction proof checker, a truth table
          checker, a Venn diagram checker — they live online and are
          linked from Canvas. They are meant to give you fast, patient
          feedback while you practice. They will not do your homework,
          but they will tell you when something is off.
        </p>
        <p>
          A note on what this book is: a working draft. You are among
          the first students to use it, and parts will be rough at the
          edges. If you spot a typo, a confusing passage, or an exercise
          that doesn't quite work, tell me. You are doing future students
          a favor, and you'll get genuine thanks.
        </p>
        <p>
          Logic is a quiet subject. It doesn't shout, and it rarely
          settles a fight on its own. But it gives you a way to slow down
          a hot argument, see what is actually being claimed, and decide
          what to do about it. That is a useful thing to be able to do.
          I hope you find this book a decent companion while you learn
          it.
        </p>
        <p>
          <line>— M.R.</line>
          <line>University of Mary Washington</line>
          <line>Summer 2026</line>
        </p>
      </preface>

    </frontmatter>

    <!--
      Part I — Arguments and Reasoning (Informal Logic)
      Maps to Baronett Ch. 1, 3 in the current PHIL 151B course; here treated
      as a unified treatment of argument identification, structure, language,
      and informal fallacies.
    -->
    <part xml:id="part-arguments">
