    </part>

    <!--
      Part IV — Inductive and Statistical Reasoning
      Goes deeper than typical intro texts; Hacking-flavored without being
      Hacking-deep.
    -->
    <part xml:id="part-statistical">
      <title>Inductive and Statistical Reasoning</title>
      <introduction xml:id="part-statistical-intro">
        <p>
          Parts I through III focused mostly on deductive reasoning:
          arguments where the premises are supposed to guarantee the
          conclusion. That work matters. It gives us the cleanest
          examples of logical structure, and it teaches habits of
          precision that carry over into everything else.
        </p>
        <p>
          But most of the reasoning we actually live with is not like
          that. A physician reads symptoms and test results. A voter
          looks at a record and tries to predict what a candidate will
          do. A scientist studies a sample and draws a conclusion about
          a population. A student checks the weather, looks at the sky,
          and decides whether to carry an umbrella. In each case, the
          evidence matters, but it does not make the conclusion certain.
        </p>
        <p>
          Part IV is about that kind of reasoning. We will study
          induction, probability, descriptive statistics, and statistical
          inference. The goal is not to turn logic into arithmetic. The
          goal is to understand how evidence can make a conclusion more
          or less reasonable when certainty is not available.
        </p>
        <p>
          This unit draws in part on Matthew Knachel's
          <url href="https://wisconsin.pressbooks.pub/logicfundamentals/"
               visual="wisconsin.pressbooks.pub/logicfundamentals/">
            <em>Fundamental Methods of Logic</em>
          </url>, an open textbook licensed under a Creative Commons
          Attribution 4.0 International License. The material here is
          adapted, reorganized, and revised for this course.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <xi:include href="chapters/ch-inductive-reasoning.ptx"/>
      <xi:include href="chapters/ch-probability.ptx"/>
      <xi:include href="chapters/ch-statistical-reasoning.ptx"/>
    </part>

